                        <span class="feature-value">Zero-Based</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Bank Sync</span>
                        <span class="feature-value check-icon">✓ (Premium only)</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Investment Tracking</span>
                        <span class="feature-value cross-icon">✗</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Bill Tracking</span>
                        <span class="feature-value cross-icon">✗</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Family Sharing</span>
                        <span class="feature-value cross-icon">✗</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p class="app-description">Created by Ramsey Solutions, EveryDollar provides a very simple, intuitive interface for zero-based budgeting. The free version requires manual entry, while the expensive premium tier adds bank syncing and financial coaching.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- PocketGuard -->
            <div class="app-card">
                <div class="app-header">
                    <div class="app-title-section">
                        <h2>PocketGuard</h2>
                        <span class="verdict-badge">Best for Overspenders</span>
                    </div>
                    <div style="font-weight:bold; font-size:1.1rem;">Free / $7.99/mo</div>
                </div>
                <div class="app-features">
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Method</span>
                        <span class="feature-value">"In My Pocket" (Disposable Income)</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Bank Sync</span>
                        <span class="feature-value check-icon">✓</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Investment Tracking</span>
                        <span class="feature-value cross-icon">✗</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Bill Tracking</span>
                        <span class="feature-value check-icon">✓</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-row">
                        <span class="feature-label">Family Sharing</span>
                        <span class="feature-value cross-icon">✗</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p class="app-description">PocketGuard focuses entirely on simplifying your finances down to one number: how much safe spending money you have left "in your pocket" after bills, goals, and necessities are accounted for.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Mint (Legacy Note) -->
            <div class="app-card" style="opacity: 0.75; background-color: var(--bg-color);">
                <div class="app-header">
                    <div class="app-title-section">
                        <h2 style="color: var(--text-secondary);">Mint (Intuit)</h2>
                        <span class="verdict-badge" style="border-color: var(--text-secondary); color: var(--text-secondary);">Discontinued</span>
                    </div>
                    <div style="font-weight:bold; font-size:1.1rem; color: var(--text-secondary);">N/A</div>
                </div>
                <p class="app-description">Mint was the pioneer of free, automated budgeting and net worth tracking for over 15 years. Intuit officially shut down Mint in early 2024, attempting to transition users to Credit Karma, prompting massive migration to alternatives like Monarch and Simplifi.</p>
            </div>

        </div>

        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>Choosing the Right Budgeting Method</h2>
            <p>Before selecting an app, it's crucial to understand which budgeting methodology works best for your brain. The software is just a tool to facilitate the method.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB):</strong> You assign every single dollar of income to a specific category (expenses, savings, debt) until you have exactly zero dollars left unassigned. It's proactive and intentional. Best apps: <strong>YNAB, EveryDollar.</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Envelope System:</strong> You allocate cash (digitally) into distinct "envelopes" for different spending categories. When an envelope is empty, you stop spending in that category. Best app: <strong>Goodbudget.</strong></li>
                <li><strong>50/30/20 Rule:</strong> A simpler framework allocating 50% to Needs, 30% to Wants, and 20% to Savings/Debt. Many categorization apps handle this well. Best apps: <strong>Monarch, Simplifi.</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Why Bank Sync Matters (Or Doesn't)</h2>
            <p>Most modern premium apps offer automatic bank synchronization. They pull your transactions daily, requiring you only to verify or categorize them. This saves immense time and prevents you from forgetting cash outlays. However, advocates of manual entry (like the free versions of Goodbudget or EveryDollar) argue that the friction of physically typing in a $5 coffee purchase makes you more acutely aware of your spending habits.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is zero-based budgeting?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Zero-based budgeting is a method where every dollar you earn is assigned a specific job, whether it's for expenses, savings, or debt payoff. At the end of the month, your income minus your expenses should equal exactly zero. Apps like YNAB and EveryDollar are built around this philosophy.</div>
